2) The first was a practical reason to compress, the second is more creative. Compression allows us to shape the envelope of sounds, by varying the attack and release and type of compressor we use (we'll come back to that). Why would that be useful? A few examples;

- A fast attack allows us to tame the front of a sound, and set it back in an arrangement. Our ears are naturally drawn to shorter sharper transients, and that can be a lovely thing. But say for example I've got a bright and transient heavy acoustic guitar, it might be distracting me from the vocal and the story of the song, a fast attack and low ratio could allow me to "set it back" behind the vocal, without turning it down or darkening it too much

- Another way we can use the envelope shaping is to bring out the body or thump in a sound. Take something like a bright snare crack, a compressor like a DBX160 will grab the front transient and soften it, and then the release curve will give the body and shell of the snare this chunky weight that can be really musical

One last comment. To maybe close out on something positive. The *WHY*

When I master I’m looking to increase connection and help things to find their true form. It’s abstract but also kind of simple all at once

@Eric Martin just showed up and I did a master for him the other day. The mix was great, honestly hard to improve on. But using RX I was able to reduce a particular type of vocal resonance, once that was tended to I was able to EQ for maybe 5% more emotional connection

if the client can't send alt lyrics - first confirm what they actually want taken out (preferably a lyric pdf with naughty words highlighted if there's a lot going on)

if there aren't any words in the session you can fly in that make sense, precisely chop out (don't forget any doubles/harms/printed verbs, doublers, or parallels)
and get creative with blurring over that gap - delay throws, reverb toss, stuttering the previous/next word, reverse reverb into it, all of the above who cares as long as it sounds dope

@Eric Martin thanks for your reply man, re: clippers vs compression......yes i am familiar with that. I dont use compression for dynamics control either....you may have heard of the "clip to zero" strategy? i do a similar thing but then output my limiters/clippers at -6db instead of 0. Its similar to what johns doing just catching peaks and not squashing the life out of everythin....mike dean does it too IIRC. 

Re: spectral shaper : I didnt actually spot jon using his spectral shaper in that 1-6khz region, i saw it in the low mids....so having heard you and @oaklandmatt both mention it ...it seems hes defo already using this high mid scoop trick then! Ill still research the maths of the lufs algo because i like to really understand the psycho-acoustics and science of these sorts of things. Im after the ultimate mix in this life, lol .....i come from underground club music, where drums and bass and a sweet vocal are everything so its a constant balance/re-balance between lows/mids and highs as i learn more advanced techniques

..re: jons mix yesterday and clipping, and you mention clipping the attack portion of a sounds adsr , did you notice how much he uses transient shapers on almost everything? v clever. Personally, i love transients and fight hard to keep them and jons trick of putting a transient shaper after a clipper/limiter has been a revelation....(thanks @oaklandmatt , that gem came from your LWMR) .....bruce swedien said compression is for children, and i believe he evangelised about not killing transients ...i love a transient shaper and a clipper ....compressor , not so much.

@oaklandmatt Great episode yesterday! 

You did leave me a little curious tho! You said, you were handing in your first ableton mix. (I hope you did a short square wave blip at the beginning and end or @BatMeckley might come after you and your not sample accurate multitracks 😅)

You said you got your vocal mix in protools and then pulled it into ableton, for practical reasons. Does that mean you bounced the wet vocal and just had a vocal track, and mixed the beat around that or did you bounce the dry vocal and recreate your chain from protools, so you’d still be able to tweak it in ableton? Curious about this workflow, because I like yourself also always produce in ableton, and record people outside of ableton.

@Josh @JakeTB that makes a lot of sense until you realize they spent two years and hundreds of thousands of pounds *at minimum* trying to find the follow up to all his first album success. I was scheduled to write with him and Aldae for this new album in July 2021 in London (he got covid and had to cancel). He later canceled a whole tour to stay in the studio and write.

Sonically it sounds very much like what we're talking about, but thinking about the business machine behind this album it sounds insane. From everything I know about making records and the business, it seems like it would be super easy for him to recut a vocal.

Something very strange happened. It doesn't add up.
